&lt;h3 id="garden-description">Garden Description&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>According to Eschebach’s plan, there was a &lt;em>portico&lt;/em> at the rear of this house that enclosed this &lt;em>peristyle&lt;/em> garden (a) on four sides. A small section of the foundation wall remains on the south end of the east side. &lt;span style="color:orange"> The &lt;em>cubiculum&lt;/em> (b) to the east of the &lt;em>atrium&lt;/em> has a garden representation on the west half of the black &lt;em>predella&lt;/em> on the south wall. It was poorly preserved but the left section shows a garden with a lattice fence and a pergola. Faint images remain of a similar pergola on the right side. The center of the painting, (which is 0.09 x 0.84 m.) has an open area with a crater perhaps serving as a fountain in a pergola. Two additional pergolas stand to either side. &lt;/span>&lt;/p>
